issue.title: Next.js SSR unhandled errors are not logged
issue.body:
### Is there an existing issue for this? - [X] I have checked for existing issues https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-javascript/issues - [X] I have reviewed the documentation https://docs.sentry.io/ - [X] I am using the latest SDK release https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-javascript/releases ### How do you use Sentry? Sentry Saas (sentry.io) ### Which SDK are you using? @sentry/nextjs ### SDK Version 7.73.0 ### Framework Version Next.js 13.5.3 ### Link to Sentry event _No response_ ### SDK Setup _No response_ ### Steps to Reproduce 1. [Install NextJS example](https://nextjs.org/learn/basics/create-nextjs-app/setup), enter project dir and init git repo (seems to be required for sentry wizard) ```bash npx create-next-app@latest nextjs-blog --use-npm --example "https://github.com/vercel/next-learn/tree/main/basics/learn-starter" cd nextjs-blog/ git init ``` 1. [Install sentry](https://docs.sentry.io/platforms/javascript/guides/nextjs/#install) ```bash npx @sentry/wizard@latest -i nextjs ``` 1. Modify the [home page](https://github.com/vercel/next-learn/blob/main/basics/learn-starter/pages/index.js) to make it SSR rather than SSG and throw an error server-side during page component render. ```javscript export function getServerSideProps () { return { props: { a: 'b', } } } export default function Home() { if (typeof window === 'undefined') throw new Error('server-side error') else throw new Error('client-side error') return
} ``` 1. Build, start, and load page at http://localhost:3000 ```bash npm run build && npm start ``` ### Expected Result I expected at least the server-side error to be logged in Sentry. I wouldn't be surprised if both a server-side and client-side error were logged per page load. ### Actual Result No errors are logged in sentry

pull_request.title: feat(nextjs): Trace errors in page component SSR
pull_request.body:
This will attach errors happening while serverside rendering page components to the corresponding transaction.

Resolves https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-javascript/issues/9152

Note: Ideally we would have a span for rendering the page and attach the error there but this would be messy to do with our current implementation. The reason is that we cannot directly grab the request transaction from within the render function because it doesn't live in the current async context. We would have to pass references or keys around and clean them up after a response has been sent so the transactions can be GCd. The mess would originate from the fact that we create spans and transactions differently depending on whether we're in a lambda environment.

We will do span creation in a follow-up PR.

commits.message: clean up

pull_request.title: meta(nextjs): Bump peer deps for Next.js 14
pull_request.body:
Bumping peer deps for version 14 of Next.js. Our integration tests are failing with Next.js 14 (https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-javascript/pull/9379) but I don't strongly believe this is something that the SDK is causing based off the error's we're seeing. We communicated this to Vercel - currently awaiting answer. E2E tests are green.

Fixes https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-javascript/issues/9380

commits.message: tests
fix(nextjs): Instrument route handlers with `jsx` and `tsx` file extensions (#9362)

fix(deno): Build Sentry dependencies for tests (#9312)

Co-authored-by: Luca Forstner <luca.forstner@sentry.io>

fix(replay): ensure `replay_id` is not added to DSC if session expired (#9359)

We noticed we still sometimes see "too long sessions", and it seems this
is because of errors being tagged with a replay long after the session
expired. After some digging, this may be because we do not check session
expiration when adding the `replay_id` to the DSC. This PR fixes this.

pako tree shaking ootb.

We don't need all the inflation stuff in our bundle.

fix(nextjs): Trace with performance disabled
pull_request.body: We guarded a lot of tracing functionality in Next.js behind `hasTracingEnabled()` which will prevent events from being traced when performance is disabled.

pull_request.title: feat(nextjs): Trace errors in page component SSR
pull_request.body:
This will attach errors happening while serverside rendering page components to the corresponding transaction.

Resolves https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-javascript/issues/9152

Note: Ideally we would have a span for rendering the page and attach the error there but this would be messy to do with our current implementation. The reason is that we cannot directly grab the request transaction from within the render function because it doesn't live in the current async context. We would have to pass references or keys around and clean them up after a response has been sent so the transactions can be GCd. The mess would originate from the fact that we create spans and transactions differently depending on whether we're in a lambda environment.

We will do span creation in a follow-up PR.
